ownedComment.body: The Use-Case Model illustrates the functionality the system must provide. It must communicate the basic functions of the system, the actors in the system, and the relationship between use cases and actors. A business use-case model may be added at a later time.
This package contains the use cases related to system administration.
This use case is started by call and mobility management related activities. It provides the capability to validate the right of a system user to work within the PBX.

This use case is started by the system administrator. It provides the capability to add, remove, or modify information regarding a system user. The information is stored in the system database so that accurate records for each user can be maintained.
This package contains all of the actors in the system.
The GSM system which enables mobile communications inside the PBX.
A person who uses a cell phone handset to access the services provided by the PBX system.
A person who accesses the system using standard POTs equipment.
A person who adds or removes users from the PBX system database.
An external system responsible for maintaining accurate records of use by each registered user.
An external telephone network which the PBX connects to, such as as ISDN.
This package contains all the use case associated with the basic calling features that the system must support. Namely, calling a subscriber inside the PBX and dialing a number outside the PBX.
This use case is started when the user dials a number outside of the PBX.
This use case is started when the user dials an extension of the PBX.
This package contains all the use case associated with advanced calling features such as short messaging service, paging, caller ID, email, voice mail, n-way calling, and call forwarding.
This package contains all use cases related to issues surrounding radio resource management, mobility management, signal strength management, cell handovers, and other GSM-based requirements.

This use case is started when a mobile subscriber powers on a wireless handset. In order to maximize the number of supported users, the system will only allocate system resources when a mobile subscriber powers-on.

This layer contains the subsystems which implement the high level administration, control, and subscriber interactions with the system. For the most part, additional features would logically belong in this layer.
This package contains model elements which implement specialized or customized hardware capabilities.

This class is a specialization of a proxy manager which manages a set of wireless handset proxies. It creates a UIListener to pay attention to the cell phone UI. It then builds fixed number of cell phone proxies, each of which imports a reference to the UIListener. When all the references have been created, any client of the manager can request a phone proxy.
Complementary array of flags to track which phone resources can be given to a device. There is a 1-to-1 mapping between devices and phone proxies, so there should not be a conflict.

This capsule enables each wireless handset proxy to safely access the UIListener. The structure of the UIAccessPoint is a "dogbone". Messages are simply passed through the capsule. The capsule is passed from the client to the server to enable communication between them. We refer to this type of communication as safe dynamic structure, because we avoid the overhead of bookeeping data structures and messages to manage the dynamics of the client server communication. Instead, we take advantage of the built-in capabilities of the RTS to manage this for us.
Allows communication between the phone proxy manager and the phone proxies.

This class utility is an arbitrary organization of constants used in the model.
This constant controls the maximum number of devices allowed in the system. A device is an abstract class which represents any number of possible original or terminal sessions.

This constant is used to specify the upper bounds on how many sessions the system will handle at any given time. The upper bounds is derived by multiplying the total number of calls in the system by the total number of sessions allowed per call.
This constant defines the upper bounds on the number of calls the system will process at any time.
This constant represents the upper bounds on the number of sessions that can be involved in a call. In order to permit n-way calling, the value of the constant must be n.

This constant represents the upper bounds on the number of extensions a single phone can have. For the purposes of this itteration, it is 1. As the system evolves to support multi-line phones as well as handsets, this number will have to increase.
This constant represents the upper bounds on the number of sessions that can appear in a single call. It is set to 3 to enable three-way calling.
This constant represents the upper bounds on the number of valid extensions the system maintains. It should be no less than the number of devices the system manages.

This constant represents the upper bounds on how many appearances an extension can present to the system. To meet the requirement that the handset never ring busy, or to insure that voice mail is reached, this number should be > 1 in production.
This constant represents the upper bounds on the number of retries the connection observer will attempt before assuming that the UI has gone down. It is part of the test harness.
This constant represents the upper bounds on the number of valid extensions the system maintains. It should be no less than the number of devices the system manages.

This package contains subsystems that implement the major domain abstractions, such as call control and device management.
This subsystem contains the classes that implement the management of hardware associated with the devices supported by the call processing system.
This class is a specialization of DialPlanData. It is used to hold phone numbers which the system treats as addresses to devices in the system.

The system must support a wide variety of devices. Each will have hardware associated with them. At least in the initial stages of development, not all hardware will be available and some hardware decisions are better deferred until latter. Thus, the development team expects to be simulating the hardware devices in software for some time to come.
In addition, even as hardware becomes available, it will be neccessary to have a mechanism to translate low-level hardware signals into high-level system signals. Thus, a requirement for hardware proxies exists throughout the lifetime of the project.
This superclass implements an abstract framework for deploying a number of specialized proxies dynamically in the system under development.

In future iterations, the system will be required to support various levels of extension configurations. For example, a call centre might want the system to hunt for a free device so the client never gets a busy signal. In order to do this, the system must separate the extension from the device. In other words, the extension access point is the only thing the system really understands. What device this is connected to is only of interest to the parties to the call.
Extension is the superclass of all extension types. Since the system will have to support more than one type of device, there must be specialized extensions.

This is a specialized subclass of a generic device address. It is intended to be used with a telephone, either wireless or fixed. This class will have to be modified further as teh system evolves to support additional advanced system features such as never ring busy, or multi-extension devices.

This is a place holder class in our current design. In this iteration, the designers decided to concentrate on the basic call processing model and to defer decisions about the transport mechanisms until later. Place holders such as this one play the role of "smart stubs" in the design. This transition is triggered if the GMSC is already in the process of allocating a channel and system resources when a new request comes in. In order to avoid race conditions, the designers have elected to serialize access to the GMSC in this way. Under load, this approach is not likely to provide the through-put required, so alternatives are be actively explored.

ownedComment.body: In this state, the GMSC can respond to either a channel request or a channel release from the wireless subscribers. Please note that right now, the GMSC does not drop requests on the floor. If a request arrives when the GMSC is occupied, it defers the request. While this is an acceptable strategy for a first pass design, some sort of flow control should be implemented so the GMSC can run at full throtle without relying on built-in RTS message defers.

An onhook signal is generated to take care of the possibility that the power down occurs in the middle of a call. If the device is idle, this signal is ignored. The system is also permitted to reclaim unused resources associated with the handset. The permission to reclaim resources is sent out at the lowest possible priority to enable the system to do this when there are free cycles.

However, until a device within the system has been reserved for the handset, the user cannot place a call. The handset proxy waits in this state until it receives a channel allocation from the provider. As far as the handset is concerned, the moment it receives confirmation, it will consider itself to be connected.

This state is the primary state of a handset when it is powered on and quiescent. Notice the "staple" pattern of transitions. This is an appropriate modelling construct for this capsule because it acts as a filter for UI events based on mode. Simply pressing a number button does not in and of itself remove the filter from that mode. Only events from the SYSTEM inform the filter when to change modes.
This state reflects the mode where the user has dialed a number and the system has located the dialed party. Only the dialing party can end the call by pressing the end button.
This state reflects the mode where both parties to the call have been connected. Only an END, dialed party release, or a PWR event will change the mode from connected to dialing.

This state reflects the mode where the handset has been dialed by another party. When the user accepts the call by pressing SND, the call is connected and the device filter reflecst that. If the call is unwanted, the can either ignore the call or power off the phone to stop the call. They cannot hit END as can the dialing party.

This package contains the use-case realizations which allow us to trace functional requirements captured in the use-case model to elements of the design model.

This is the use-case which realizes the requirement that the user be able to place a call to a valid extension inside the PBX.
This is the party to the call that goes off-hook and dials the number.
This is the party to the call that is dialed. The phone will ring in until the dialing party goes on-hook or the dialed party goes off-hook.

The call controller is responsible for bringing both parties to the call into a dynamic relationship for the duration of the call. When either party goes on-hook, the call controller releases the resources associated with the call.
This object assembles both parties to the call into a dynamic relationship. When one or the other party goes on-hook at the end of the call, it allows the system to reclaim the resources for reuse.
This is the database of valid phone numbers that the system supports. The responsibility of the database is to maintain and validate the phone numbers.

This processor is the target that the system will be actually be deployed on. By retargeting the model early and often, designs can be validated in the actual environment in which they will be run. Note that the information on the Details tab is for demonstration purposes only. It must reflect the actual address of the target board and target server in your environment.

A processor is a hardware component capable of executing programs. You can further define a processor by identifying the processes execute on it. In this case, the NT processor is intended to allows developers to verify the design in an environment with a complete set of development tools.
